                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/6723</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum Dictated in the Office of the Assistant Secretary
                        of State by the British Ambassador</hi>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d180fn3">Paraphrase of a telegram from The Hague, dated July
                        16, 1917.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>The Hague</placeName>, <date
                        ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1917-07-16">July 16, 1917</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>Austrian Legation stated that in the course of the negotiations between the
                    Emperor of Austria and Kaiser <persName corresp="#p_WII1">Wilhelm</persName>,
                        <persName corresp="#p_HFMPB1">Hindenburg</persName> had declared that under
                    no circumstances could Germany adopt a program of a peace without annexation.
                    Disruption and national bankruptcy would be the necessary consequence of a peace
                    in which Germany recognized the commercial independence of Belgium.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
